Great in theory but the companies and their employees really push the envelope with what is allowed. I live near a Canada Line station and often there are 6-10 or more car share cars outside my house meaning I have to park down the block. I've phoned to complain and they were very rude. They said it's their right to park anywhere and that in any event it's my neighbours using them. Well that isn't true because I've seen Car2Go employees deliver cars to in front of my house, 5 or more all in a row and then they pull up in their van and start cleaning the cars. That is definitely not the intent of the park anywhere rule. There is also always garbage left outside the cars (probably because people don't want to be charged for leaving it in the car so they throw it on the boulevard). Also I've witnessed a lot of dangerous driving from car share vehicles, not sure if because the people don't drive enough so are out of practice or because they're on a clock and want to pay as little money as possible. Also I find many don't care about parking rules. I've often seen car share cars parked in front of fire hydrants or too close to a corner or in no parking zones. They probably just figure someone else will come along and use the car before a bylaw or police office can ticket it. In normal neighbourhoods there's no issue with them but something has to be done around transit hubs because it is absolutely ridiculous the number of cars constantly parked outside my house, in a "Residents Only" zone I might add.

If it was possible to drive into Richmond and park anywhere, that would honestly be a dream come true for a lot of users I would think. Richmond holds Richmond center, lots of food places and accessibility there would be great beyond having to take the skytrain. Plus, most of parking in Richmond is already free or at least for a significantly lower cost than it would be in places such as downtown Vancouver or ubc. Furthermore, one of the biggest reasons why I think people use carsharing services such as yourself, is for the convenience. However, being able to drive to a skytrain station, then having to park, wait for the train/bus, then get on the train/busmakes it not only unecessarily costly (could have just taken one bus instead and completely ignored the carsharing services available, reducing the need for carsharing) and not very efficient if you are going to a place in Richmond or even Burnaby that is beyond the walking radii of skytrain stations, and thus must resort to busses. Being able to have the "freedom" to travel should include Vancouver's neighbouring cities as a way to truly endorse freedom without consequence of higher costs for the same "freedom" that's marketed to simply the Vancouver district. Finally, distance wise, Richmond is indeed a bit out of the way for more people coming from UBC, Downtown, and even East Van. This means that it would cost them ~20-30 minutes to get from there to Richmond. This means (as at the end of the day Car2Go is an incredibly successful business) there is great profit to be made in these lengthy trips. That's all. Otherwise, great customer service, wonderful rates and I am incredibly pleased with joining. I have referred multiple friends to join and they have been just as pleased as I have been with how easy, pain free and fun car2go is.

I have been deeply disappointed that none of the carsharing networks have made any attempt to reduce the carbon emissions associated with their operations.  If anything, the opposite is true.  When Car2Go started, it had some electric SmartCars in addition to its fossil fuel powered SmartCars.  Not only did it eliminate the electric cars, it added large Mercedes sedans to its fleet.  Modo has a handful of electric vehicles, has not increased their number as the size of its fleet expanded, and has created rules that make the use of those electric vehicles unnecessarily difficult.

I would recommend that local and provincial governments give the carsharing networks a choice:  create plans for transitioning - with our help - to ZEV fleets, or we will create our own carsharing network and freeze you out of the market.
